\rtlch\fcs1 \af1 \ltrch\fcs0 \f1\insrsid4729\charrsid16072257 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-461\li461\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin461\itap0\pararsid4729 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You were telling me when you started at a firm as an apprentice?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 When you started at 
a firm as an apprentice, this particular firm at fourteen you start at six and if you was late twice in a week you'd - they'd wait for you like quarter hour, that was from eight - from six ' til eight o'clock if you miss that they'd wait for you coming in
 
- in at half past eight, with a handcart and they - all, all apprentices there waiting for you and if you had - had a bus or tram - it's the trams then, get off the tram they'd all be bashing on you, get you and throw you in the trough at - corner of Cros
s Lane.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Just for the hell of it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
That's for - that was the - that was the - one of the traditions of the firm to - with an apprentice for being lazy - late twice. And if there was three they'd have three handcarts and all the apprentices, in thos
e days there was always loads of apprentices, it was all cheap labour then and they'd wait for the horse trough and throw you in, it meant you going home or working with your wet things wet through going in the fire hole and getting them dry.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 What did you do when you finished your apprenticeship?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
And at Christmas - no, at Christmas time the - the first year at apprentice you had to sing or recitation and you'd get on one of the old drills or any machine and everybody - it was like a - a party, th
ere's no such things as Christmas dinners in those days, and you get on a machine and give a song and if they thought you was lousy, whether you was lousy or good you'd get all blacking bags out of the foundry you know they used to do the old black lead, 
you'd get those and they'd wet and they'd throw 'em at you, buckets of water. You - you'd - your clothes was ruined.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 This was your first job when you were an apprentice?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 That was the first year - that was your first year apprentice at - the first
 Christmas when you're an apprentice they did that - everybody had to sing or say recitation and anybody a bit nervous, well - you'd stand there and case well it - you'd - get an idea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 How did you get your first job, did you get it through a Labour Exchange?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No, I got it though an uncle who was a crane driver there and he spoke -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Which firm was this?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Lancaster and Tongues, I only worked at one firm, yes, Lancaster and Tongues and this uncle of mine was a crane driver and he daid to me
 father he'd get me a job there. Well I didn't know what I was going in for. Heartbroken. Starting at six o'clock, always been used to getting up at half past eight in the morning, you know, school hours and starting up there used to break my heart gettin
g there. And then -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You used to start at six?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Six. Half past five then. Sixty hour -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Do you remember what your wage was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Five shilling a week my first wage.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you think it was a fair wage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 I didn't. No. Well you - six - spends sixpence a week then wasn't it. Penny-penny in the shilling then. But I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you give any of the money in at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well me father used to give me sixpence back - give him the five shilling you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 How did you get on with the people you worked with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well - well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Apart from being thrown in the horse trough?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Every body got that, it couldn't - but I always remember when I was late twice I never turned up, I used to have the day off. It wasn't so often. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 But as a whole you liked the people did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Yes. But - going to work in the morning there's always these confectioners shops where you could have a cup of coffee and a bun.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 And you used to stop?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Now and again, well if I had any money, it's not o
ften but I mean to say you couldn't do much on sixpence. Used to get to work and start work. Then you'd have your - morning you'd have your breakfast half past - eight o'clock 'til half past eight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 How did your employer treat you and how did you feel about him?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Just thinking how the employer treat - just - there was just - I used to be afraid of the old secretary that they had there, he was a bit of a bully but - management weren't so bad, they weren't so bad management. I'm talking about like w
hen I first started. I'm not talking about as - as got older, you know, where I could stand up for myself, it was different.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you like the work as a boy apprentice?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No, I didn't, no, I never liked it because I used to try and get to work as a
 motor - I always wanted to be a motor driver, that were my - yes, to be out, I thought it was wonderful to be out driving a motor car in those days, sightseeing and getting paid for being - going here and going everywhere.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Getting paid for enjoying life you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Enjoying, I though but as you get older you see different don't you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you belong to a trade union?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 I belonged to the - the old Steam Engine Makers then in those days, they come to another - there was three engineering unio
ns then, there was the steam engine makers and then another union, then they amalgamated together, what they call the A.E.U. then - now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you take part in any of its activities?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No, I did'nt - no, there was nothing - nothing of any then. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Before 1918 did you feel that employers and workers had the same interests or different ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Now 1918 I'd be about - I'd only been working - four - sixteen then. I started 1916, I'd be eighteen then. But more than that, you were afraid of them really, you respected 'em didn't you when you was a youth.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 When you were young did you feel there was a division of interest amongst workers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 In those days at that wage - I think the money was - I thought all along for years that the employers making money out of me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You've always felt this have you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 I have up to retiring now, I've always thought that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Some people say that in those days there was a great division between trained craftsmen and other workers, did you feel that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Well a craftsman, a labourer was a - he was a labourer in those days. There was a big difference, yes. Yes, a craftsman was somebody. Oh yes, he - he was respected looked up on in those days, a craftsman. If you said you was an engineer years ago - peop
le - you were somebody. But to meal that's gone now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 How many years did you live in the house where you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 I - I was born in a shop - Whit Lane, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 How long did you live there, do you know?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Oh must have been - three, say there years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Then you moved on to Cook Street?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
No, I moved on to Thursfield Street. And then was there a few years and I spent half of my life or part of my life on the River Irwell. Yes, that's - that was my on the River Irwell. It was near the Ir
well that got me - that was when the time I took an interest in swimming. Every time - of evenings or anytime was always on the side of the River Irwell, on those islands or the other side of the race course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Swimming in the river?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No, not swimm
ing, just playing, paddling. As a very young child that was - well, well we'd nowhere else to play barring a game of cricket but we always made our way to the River Irwell and getting on that sewer that went underneath, there was an old sewer there where 
y
ou could - into the Clarence Hotel. And we used to walk - yes, we used to walk underneath there - one of these about four foot diameter. And we used to walk through there and so far we'd get frightened and turn back. But it used to go to the Clarence Hote
l in Whit Lane but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Where did you live the longest then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Cook Street. Cook Street, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Can you tell me how many rooms there were at cook Street and how they were used?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 There was two rooms - two bedrooms. Two bedrooms and there was - me sister had the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Three down?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Three down, that's right, three down. It was a two bedrooms and - sisters had the back bedroom, two sisters and the men, me father and all the rest in the - in the other room.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Do you know why you moved from these houses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Oh well, why we removed it's to be nearer for me father's work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Get nearer Horsefall and Bickhams?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Yes, it wasn't - it wasn't so far off you know but he got half the distance again, so starting at six o'clock he thought he'd 
get a bit nearer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You told me he was a labourer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 He's a labourer yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did he always do that type of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Yes. Well he had fifty years there, well just under fifty years then his eyesight started going and he finished then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You don't remember him ever being out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No, but - he was always broke. Always broke. Never any money. Always broke. Well, five children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Where did your father come from actually?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 He come from Radcliffe. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Where was your mother from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Warrington.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did she work at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No. No, she couldn't really, not with five children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 But you told me she ran a tripe shop?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 She ran a tripe shop but I - I couldn't just say how long we ran that tripe shop. It couldn't h
ave been so long, I think I was born in the tripe shop then I came along, she had a bad time with me and then - she got T.B. see so it - I can't remember me mother. Can't remember her, well when she died she was three, the only thing I can remember is get
t
ing the slipper, this is just one that I remember, getting one of me slippers and there's a - a blackjack in it. That's the only thing I can remember that shop. I don't know why I remember that. I was scared and in those days nothing - the house was full 
of 'em. The whole house.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 And yet it was a business wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Yes, but in the old - at the back in the old houses it was full of 'em, these houses. And they still are down on the road.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 That's the only memory you have of home as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 That's - of the shop. I never remember me mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Not at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you just live on your own in the house in Cook Street?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No, all me - all me sisters -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you have any relatives with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No, me sisters - we all lived together then in Cook Street, none of 'em were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3093926 Married}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662  then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You had no relatives or lodgers living with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You had four men in one room and you say you never had blankets?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 We never had - might just have a bit of an army sheet but we always had old overcoats over you for bedding.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Was your washing done at home or sent out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
No. The washing was always done at home. Me sister, she was fourteen when me mother died and she practically what brought me up. But the washin
g they used to do it in the old - fire boiler, get the fire going, if you had any trouble washing never hardly got done 'til later on in - in the day, but you had to stoke up - get up at six o'clock and get the old boiler going. And she always put -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did she have any help at all, your sister, or did she do it herself?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No, me younger sister just - that was only help.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did your father help in the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Yes, he - he did -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did he help undress you children or anything like that to help your older sister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Do you know - no, I don't think so. No, I don't think me father did anything, he - his job was a hard job and when he came home me sister - this sister was like the mother, the one that's fourteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did he help put you to bed or read to you or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
No, I never - I never had that in my life. I never - I never knew what a Christmas present was. Never had any, we didn't - didn't know what Christmas - Christmas way any - every other day - every day life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you have anything special for birthdays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
No, never had a birthday. Never. The only - no, the only birthday I had - ever had was at twenty-one when I got a watch and that was from Blackpool, one of these one of these - on the front - auctioneers, th
ey'd got two watches, a ladies watch and - what's supposed to be a gold watch. That was my twenty-first birthday present.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You never remember a present otherwise?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Never - the only time Christmas presents we ever got was when you bought your own a
nd I used to buy one of these German repeaters, sixpence, ha'penny - I always remember that. Never. Never got toys.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you have any jobs to help in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 I used to go errands. I always went the errands, shopping, chip shop. Penn'orth of ch
ips or - two penn'orth or chips and it was always chip shop and - running for the bread. I did - errands I did. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did the others have to help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Yes, all had to do a bit, sweeping up and cleaning, many a time I'd have half a day off from schoo
l as I got a bit older before I left school I'd have Friday afternoon off and get on me hands and knees and scrub the floor. That was one job I did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 The others didn't do anything at all?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well they - they'd started work then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you have to go to bed at a certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No. There was no - there was - there was no limit to the bed I could - I used to stop up for eleven o'clock at night.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Who put you to bed then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Nobody.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You put yourself to bed always?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Barring when I was really young, it must have been me sister.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Where did you bath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well, tell you truth, I - I can't remember ever having a bath when I was young. Used to just - can't remember baths, we never did -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You didn't have a bathroom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No bat
hroom, no, it was just a washdown. That's - as I got older it was the canal and the River Irell, used to go - I used to go - paddling and swimming in the - as I got round about the ten - tenish that's what got me swimming.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Where did the family eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well - we had the two - three rooms downstairs, it was the middle room. In the middle room, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you ever eat in another room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Where did your sister cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Cooked on the fire. It was one of those coal fires with the ove
n at the side. And every time you had to - took a bit of cleaning out and get the old rake and rake it out and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 She didn't use gas at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No, we - we never had such a thing as a gas stove. All our lives up to getting }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3093926 Married}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 . I lived while I got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3093926 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 . We never had a gas stove up to being }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3093926 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 .
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Tell me about the meals, what time was breakfast eaten and how many were there and what food you had and everything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well - they started - they start - they started at six o'clock in the
 morning, me two sisters and me father but me father always took sandwiches to work, he never came home for his breakfast and me brother, he -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 He didn't have breakfast before he left?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Not at six o'clock, no. No. Then me sister used to dash home 
at - I think it was eight o'clock and come and have breakfast but - you have to knock me up many a time, I'd slept on and got to come down to get your own breakfast all within half an hour.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 What did you have, can you tell me about meals in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Well there's never - well it was jam and - I don't remember had jam, jam was a luxury to me. It was just - bit of bread and butter and a tomato.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Was there something special on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Sunday? Now and again me father'd go to the butchers 
or late on at Pollits late on a Saturday night and get a bit of steak. Well steak was as cheap as - in those days and now and again we might have steak for Sunday mornings breakfast. Sunday mornings breakfast I remember having steak. At occasions - well i
t was more like a - a stew, I can't remember having roast me Sundays dinner. It was only a sister that did any cooking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 What did you usually have for dinners, you told me you had biscuits when you came in from school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well that was - that was in the working hours - chips or biscuits, penn'orth of biscuits or friend bananas.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 For dinners?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Yes. I used to go shopping and - Freddy Bananas and in the evenings late on when me father came home from having a drink, I was still at school, go - ac
ross - quarter of mile for quarter of cheese at eleven o'clock at night. We'd have nothing in. Bit - that was bit of cheese for breakfast time next morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You told me about bread too didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Bread, yes, we used to go up for bread to - Broad - I remember the pie.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Eight - eight and eleven we owed to this - these people when we lived in Loughson Road then we moved a mile away and every dinner time I'd to go or for pies, this mile distance in the dinner hour and get this bread and that w
as all on tic and we did that for a few years, up to me leaving school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You told me your father couldn't afford to pay the bill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 He couldn't have paid - he couldn't afford to pay the bill.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 What about tea meals, did you have a dinner at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
No. It was always half past five chips at chips. Nearly always chips. We - we never did - well - when anybody's been working from six o'clock in the morning, I was a schoolboy, everybody'd started work they was all - there was no cooking going on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No baking bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
No. No. I used to go to an aunts of mine, I had an aunt that used to cook and do you know you'd see them on a Sunday morning, they'd cook pies and you'd see 'em all on the - hard table, wash top table and I used to - I used to 
water - I used to water at the mouth on I saw these nice pies there and think that we was going home to nothing. And she said -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 She never gave them you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Never. I never remember - me aunt giving me - and that was me father's sister.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did no one help you, when you were left an orphan did no one help your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
I never - I never remember getting any help at all. I had an aunt that lived down in - Salford, if wanted a pair of shoes we used go see her, a secondhand pair of shoes on High St
reet. This was when we lived in Whit Lane - when we lived in Wilton Road. Had to go down there for a secondhand pair of shoes off High Street and had to go to me aunt's and she'd get them on the tic, she was - stand in 'til Friday, me father could go down
 and pay her. But - never no-
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You never got help from neighbours at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Not - not at all. I can't remember any help. None whatever.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No relations helped, did you have relations near to home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Yes, all lived in Whit Lane but - they was a
ll going out to work barring just a couple of aunts, the one that did all the baking but she was too mean to - and nothing. I used to go and see an old grandma on a Saturday night and she'd be - with a pan of potatoes with a couple of - having her supper,
 
she'd put a couple of potatoes on the fire, boil 'em and that'd be the old lady's supper but never offered to - would you like one for your supper. No, that was the old grandmother, I can only remember one grandmother, I can never remember any grandfather
'
s. That was the old grandmother, and never offered. I used get a ha'penny - ha'penny off an uncle of mine on the Friday night, ha'penny on a Saturday and a ha'penny on a Saturday. I used to get three ha'pence a week. Ha'penny in those days was something. 
That was me spends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 What did you spend it on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 I - I didn't spend a lot, I was very - I used to save up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You didn't go out at all and spend your money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well used to buy toffees, ha'porth of toffees and - then for fun, the - was very mis
chievous when I was a schoolboy, we used to go gangs of boys and - and - the shops in those days used to have shutters up, wooden shutters. Wooden ones, and there was always a hole in the - they'd have to put the bolt through. And one - when I come to thi
nk back it was a blooming mean trick and we used to push a stick through and knock all the tin stuff off the shelves. Yes. And we thought that was great but when I come to think now it was blooming mean.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 How did you get on with your brothers and sisters as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Well it was me - me oldest brother I was never keen on but me sisters - and me oldest sister, the one that brought me up, was never keen on. But me sister that's living today, we always got on well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Was there any-one you were especially close to as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Me brother - me sister - me other - the one that was here, me other sister. See, they was like me but me sister was a bit sharp, the oldest one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Who did you play with as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well, played with the - the boys - youngsters outside.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Neighbours, not your brother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Neighbours. Oh never played together, no, there was too much difference between me brother and I.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Where did you play, did you play in the street or in the house?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 The river - on the 
stream. Well it was more on there, there was Douglas Green in those days and the fair before those houses were on the - Littleton Road before - before you go over the bridge.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 What things did you play at?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well we used to play in the streets and -
 jumping - well - jumping on one another's backs, one'd stand up against a wall, you know. I don't know what they call it, somebody jumps. Leap-frog, then - then somebody - then the other one'd sit - as long as you could - you might get about six young me
n
 on your back - six boys on your back. Then used to play hoppy - hoppy - what they call Hoppy Johnny. Hopping. We used to play Hoppy Johnny. This - this - this is right, Hoppy Johnny. We always called it Hoppy Johnny, we used to - and there's be somebody 
in the road, be somebody in the middle of the road like and he'd dash and knock you down and he'd be on one leg.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Were you allowed to get dirty when you played?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Oh yes, I don't - I was - was never clean.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you get into trouble when you got dirty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Never got into trouble.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Were you allowed to play with anyone you pleased or did your father ever stop you playing with certain children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No. I played with anybody. I - there was no control in our house. It was free and easy. If I wa
s that way I could have got into loads of trouble. None at all. Me father -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You said you brought yourself up didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 But - yes, we all did, we all brought ourselves up. Just me sister at fourteen. She was the oldest one. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you have any hobbies or keep pets or collect anything - I know you didn't do gardening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
No, we had no garden then, no. I used - I was fond of walking, that was about my only - used to keep cats. And we couldn't - couldn't afford to keep them tell you truth but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 So how did you keep them?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well - it was just a bit of bread and - well tell you the truth we had a proper dirty habit then, chewing bread and giving it the cat. Yes.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Why did you chew it first?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 The cat - well you see with the 
cat and then bread in the tripe my father - now and again the cat'd get treated you see, a few - few tripe parings and that lasted all week - apart from the chewed bread. Honestly we used to put chewed bread. That was a dirty habit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 It had one feed of tripe and that lasted all the week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
That was - that lasted all the week, yes. Then there was always any cats - any she cats whose - the kittens was always born in the bottom drawer and the bottom drawer was never cleaned out. I can - can't remember it ever being cleaned out, you know.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 And the cat always had its kittens there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
All her kit - there, kittens then - if you got too many or you wanted to get rid of the cat I can remember one time me pal he worked at Walton's Bleach Works and me f
ather said, could you get rid of this cat Joe? He said, I'll treat you. So he came one time with a bag, went to the Walton's Bleach Works, the Irwell was there, the waterfall, dropped it in the well that went into the river, he came back, before he came b
a
ck the cat'd come back, wet through. It'd escaped. He'd dropped it in the river but it got out and the bag was supposed to be tied with a brick in, that's how they used to drown cats. Put it in a canvas bag, tie the top and he's supposed to have done that
, drown the cat, it came back, it was back before he came.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Were you in a youth club or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No. It was older times when I was about thirty I took interest in boxing, I used to go boxing but not in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you do any fishing or walking, you said you went walking didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well I did lots of -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you do bicycling or fishing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Bicycle - well, you couldn't afford a bike then but now and again did a little bit of - we did a bit - bit of fishing one time, went to Pic
kmere but I was getting about round the eighteen mark then and we went fishing. And this was the same chap that - supposed to have drowned the cat. Went fishing with him, he intended staying the - the night, we got to Pickmere and - went - ordered to stay
 the night at one of these little - houses there. And we got on the lake and - started fishing, we fell asleep. The two of us. Time we wakened up there's a fish at the end - end of the line.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You took part in sports you said?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well that was the on
ly - the only time we never went fishing. We came back then, we never went back there. Another mean trick. We cleared off, the weather was started going dull we thought, oh we'd go home. We came back home, never bothered about the landlady what we'd booke
d these - this bed to stay the night, we came back home from Pickmere. Then I did motor - motor biking but bear in mind I was twenty -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 When you were a child at school what sports did you do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well I used to be fond of cricket then but never joined
 - never good enough to play school, but I used to play on the old Croft. This is when I lived at Littleton Road I played on the old croft in Whit Lane and - it was cricket and football then, I was very keen on football.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you ever go to theatres as a child, music halls or cinemas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
No. When I was at school the only place I ever went to - yes, you used to go to Garden Street picture house, now and again me father'd take me, tuppence. I think it was tuppence and Saturday afternoon was a penny and
 a comic paper. Then sometime you used to get a bit of toffee.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You told me you got threeha'pence pocket money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 That's about the only limit - that's the only thing I know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You went to a theatre once while you were at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Bonds. Whe
n I was - when I was at school and I went with a chap named Newbury, finished up in prison, and went see the - the Gold Diggers. That was at the old Victoria Theatre and I can remember it - large piece of - well - we threw it on the stage and the stage, b
ang, bang, bang, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 This was a friend of yours, Newbury?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
This friend of me, yes, he is father had a bicycle shop in Whit Lane but he finished up a - he was a seafaring man, he finished up in jail. He had a big family, old Newbury. I think 
that was all his time was booked on, not repairing bikes. And they were a terrible family. Dirty - it was dirtier than our house, theirs. It was. And she must have had no time to clean up. Oh what a family. Now then - U used to knock about round Maud Stre
e
t and we used to live - a corner shop there, an old lady had it, when I come to think I think what blooming mean tricks, what we used to do, we'd stand round the corner and she'd like move us on, make a noise and - sometimes one'd move up on the door and 
o
ne'd creep in and - down below so she couldn't see us, then one'd ask for ha'porth of toffee or ask for an empty box, then he'd walk out, the old lady walking back in the shop and the one there started - and when I come to, you know, what a damned - that'
s was a lad's trick. Well one'd stop in the shop and maybe - soon as the old lady gone back in the house, he's behind the counter, stealing and we'd be outside - enjoying the loot when it came out. Clarkes - Clarkes and Goes. The fighters. Clarke\rquote 
s and - on the Irish road, they lived at the first house in the Irish Road and the Goes lived at the other end and every -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Why was it called the Irish Road, were they all Irish?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 There's - no, but - they must have been Irish years ago but there was a lot o
f Irish but the - the Goes was a fighting family and the - who was the other family, who did I say at the end - Clarke\rquote 
s. There was an awful family. Dandy little fellow like myself, old Clarke. And the sons were only small, one had been a jockey. Apprentice jockey but he - he got too heavy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 They were always in trouble with the police?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Oh always fight - always fighting. Every Saturday - Friday, Saturday night. Some night -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You remember this as a child do you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 I remember that, yes, there
 was always rows. And Maud Street, I had an aunt that lived in Maud Street, she was - used to fight her husband. She had more black eyes off her husband - her husband - he husbands a big fellow that worked down the pit, he was a charge hand, is it a charg
e hand, a chorter master we used to call them, chorter - but he used to come home having a drink at Yeb Roscoes in Whit Lane there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Yeb Roscoes was where they paid out the men who worked in the pit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Yeb Roscoes yes. It was a flag - flagged floor.
 Used to come out of there, he had a pint or two, come out of there and his wife was only a little woman, that was my aunt and we used to fight like hell. And all - the street'd be up - make any difference - he'd fight, he'd give her a blooming - and she'
d
 fight him but she never had any chance. He was such a big fellow but she used to stick up of him. And - and - many a time on the croft there was another fellow, another - he was a boiler man, fireman at the - one of the pits, he'd fight anybody when he g
o
t on this croft. He'd throw his coat off in middle of the croft. I'll fight it - come on, bring the police, and he'd stand there and he had bit cross-eyed, you know, when he'd few pints and - fight anybody. But the Goes family, now their father was a boil
er man - a fireman, and the son was a fireman but there's some of Goes living yet.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 When you were a child do you remember thinking of some people as being a rough family and some being respectable and why do you think this was?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well if - if there
 was fighting and - always falling out you - you'd think they was rough wouldn't you. You - you take them for being rough. My next door neighbours he was a collier, he was always falling out, I don't know why.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 And you thought of them as rough?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 I thought of them as rough.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 What about the families you thought of as respectable?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Oh well, there was a lot of clean living people. Tidy people, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Many people divide society into different social classes or groups before 1918, did yo
u think of some people belonging to one group and some to another and can you tell me what the different ones were, the different classes before 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 The shop - I did, I think a shopkeeper was real - a class - on their own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Why did you think this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well they seemed to be making - having a shop and selling things and - you always thought they had money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 What class would you think you belonged to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 I was a working class.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 What sort of people would you say belonged to the same class as yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 They - what do you mean, my friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 All the people who were in the same class as yourself, you think of yourself as working class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 All my friends was working classes, all my friends. But there's just one or two as I got a
 bit older I remember that I always thought them - as a good class 'cos they worked in office.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You always thought of office people as better class did you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Office workers, I always thought of them as better classes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 How did you see the difference, how would it show?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
'Til I got older I thought - well, always dressed up clean. I used to be coming home - home from work in overalls and I used to meet them, if they was only working at the Co-op, a shopkeeper, I always they was - one way - 
they was better than me, all dressed nice and clean. Turning out at night time, nice clean hands where I had dirty hands, I couldn't get them clean, coming home in overalls. Used to feel ashamed of myself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Would it show in their homes too do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Yes. Yes. I think it did, yes. I think if you - if you got in a family where there was office workers the home was cleaner than you got in one where there was all - manual workers. By the way, I always thought then - such as railway, they used to c
ome home dirty, there's no such things as having a canteen and having a wash up. They used to come home dirty and - and the smell of it - the grease. I used to come home smelling with me overall. We never had them cleaned like - clothing. Not the same as 
t
oday, I've got a white pair I used to put - when I was young I never thought of cleaning your clothes. There was no such things as taking them to the dry cleaners then. Whit Lane area was to me, there's such as - like Whit Lane but all round there was poo
r to me. But - you got round Dunville Street and just round the \endash  Indigo Street, they seemed a better class of people. The streets was nice and quiet.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 And yet it was all in the same little area?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 In the same area, and when you went on Gerald Road 
like - Romney Street and you went further along round by the car sheds you met those houses there, now -that was - different class of people there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Can you describe the difference in the streets, as you saw them as a child, better houses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well t
hey was better houses - well a lot of 'em was better houses like round the - it was newer property wasn't it. But near where I lived the old houses but they seemed people that kept them clean. Now our house was a real - having no mother check on it.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Your dad had a hard time didn't he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
He had a hard life - he did have a hard life you see. And then there was people on our road that always thought they was - they had their mothers there, they'd everything, the sons, there's lads like me kept nice and tidy. I used to get
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You remember people who felt superior do you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Oh yes. When I saw some of me neighbours in a way, they was always like - when they had a mother made a big difference in a family. They could - kept 'em nice and clean, their 
clothes - they always had better clothes than me. I didn't even have one of these coloured jerseys, do you remember when you used to have a jersey at one time, schoolboys. Used to have a jersey like that, you call 'em pullovers now. I never had one of tho
se. I used to envy the boys at school with a jersey with a jersey on. In never had - didn't know what it was. Never had a decent pair of shoes. Never had a pair of football boots in me life up to - twenty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 But you never had to go barefoot did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Well I always had big holes in me stocking. I've seen - I've seen young lads flogged with - a father - belts round, take 'em off and belt the - the sons. My friends - pals. Belted with a belt. The father'd take the belt - firemen, they'd take their belt 
off and - and belt 'em. That was the Goes family, I've seen the Goes family belting - any - on the Irish Row. Now wonder they call it the Irish Row.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You think this was why it was called the Irish Row?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Yes. Oh very poor - very poor. And the doors
 was always open. The doors - that's in a poorer area down - near the Pendleton pit and Irish Row and Egerton Street and all round there the doors was always open. People walked right in, there was no knocking at the door, they just seemed to walk right i
n one another's houses. And that's -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Were they immigrants on the Irish Row?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No. No. No, there was one or two Irish on there and it got the Irish Road. But there's very old houses, they've gone now. Very old.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Do you remember being brought up to treat some people differently from others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 I was - no, no, no, never brought up, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You were never told to touch your cap or anything like that to anyone?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No, but I used to notice some of me pals, as I got a bit older, respect and it g
ot me doing the same way, touching his cap when he met anybody. The fellow named Leonard Potter. He was very polite and he always - I got -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Do you remember calling anyone sir or master or madam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Yes. Not madam but - sir. Pretty often at work. Sir.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Do you remember anyone calling your father this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Sir - no. Never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Where you lived in Whit Lane who were considered the most important people and why were they considered important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well they - there was a - Mr Huges, he was a very
 important man, the undertaker. Not because he was an undertaker but he was a respected man. He was a J.P. He was a respected man. I've a photograph upstairs with him and he had it with him in a football team.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Why was he considered important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 We
ll - he was - everybody - he had money, and I suppose it was important then if you had money. And he was a J.P. and he was a Superintendent at Enys Street and he was always respected with everybody.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Do you remember anyone else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Then -Godberts th
at in the Clarence Hotel, we all took them to be - somebody. There was big hotel there in the old - he had a family of five daughters and they all seemed above anybody else, you never mixed with the - those -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Why?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well they - they never mixed wi
th the local people only those that went in as customers. Then they was behind the bar but they always move - if there's going - you wouldn't see them at street corners same as when we came out of Enys Street chapel and stood talking, never find the Godbe
rs. They always moved.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Who do you think the teachers mixed with? Who do you think the shopkeepers mixed with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 I don't know about shopkeepers, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Who do you think the teachers mixed with then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 The teachers didn't live round our - all went away, one lived in -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 What about the clergy, who did they mix with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well I only went - I only went to Enys Street. Old Mr - old Mr Hughes used to mix with his customers.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Who would employers mix with, when you first started work did you ever see any of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Can you tell me what sort of people went to church and what sort of people went to chapel and what you observed was the difference between them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well there was only - those that went to Enys Street was just the average people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 What about the people that went to St George\rquote s
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
No different to me. Didn't notice, no. No, there was only - church people thought the same there, St Georges and - against such as Enys Street.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you remember any difference between them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No, never. No. No, I went to Enys Street, I went there 'til I was about eighteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Round where you lived did all the people in the working class have the same standard of living or were there different standards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No, they was all - to me they was all about the same standard.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You didn't notice any difference in them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No. Bear in mind some kept themselves better than others but the standard was just the same.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You told me earlier some people thought themselves superior?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Oh well - yes. You got one or two like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You felt there was a difference between craftsmen and labourers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Oh there was a difference in - yes -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 What do you think it was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well - you'd see - you'd - no, you'd serve your time
 and in those days when you serve your - when you're serving your time you got a poor wage. But - them as is going to be labourers got fabulous money some way or another, nearly three times your wages. But when you come to be a craftsman you got the big d
ifference and you thought you was - I'm a tradesman and he's only a labourer and that went a lot in those days.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You thought it was very important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Yes. But there was always - plenty - always got plenty of money when - if you went to be a laboure
r you know they always got better paid than anybody being a - an apprentice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 That would only be to start of course?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Yes. No, like up to - up to about twenty-one. When - when a chap came out of time. You see, when - when you come out of your time
 you'd - twenty-one in those days - our firm - you got three months notice. They'd finished with you then. They'd let you serve your time, they'd give you three months notice and out you went.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Why did they do this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well they - they thought you'd
 serve your time, you've got to go and get experience elsewhere and you see out you went. They had - they had no work of you. That was what they call the good old days. You'd serve your time and if you was unlucky - I went to the bonding warehouse then, w
o
rking there, labouring, after serving me time. Me brother got ma - he was a foreman there and he got me labouring, I went trucking after serving my time. About two pound a week - two pound for a week. And then - I did the three months there, I had to call
 
at the old firm and - they started me back. I went back yes. Me first job as - going on the trial tips then, they were short handed, they'd gone busy the firm but that was a lot - all engineering firms did that then. And if you hadn't got the job out you 
went, you'd finish. You'd be on the dole then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Do you think in those days it was possible to move from one class or group to another, move up in the world?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No, not as - as it is today.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You didn't think they could move up at all when you were young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well you never had the opportunity. I never had.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Do you remember anyone moving up in the world?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Who - my friend. But that was later on in life. When we was young, when - when Bert Taylor was twenty - my friend went to South America
 but he's twenty - about twenty-one when he went to - he did well in life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 But as a boy you don't remember anyone moving up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Do you remember anyone going down in the world and what caused it? When you were a boy you don't remember anyone moving up in the world?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Well I know - I know - yes, Mr Evans, Will Evans the manufacturing chemist of Cook Street, he was then, he's in Eccles now. Now he was only - he came to Enys Street, he was only the average boy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 How do you think he did it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Study. Study. He had a good home. Education that did him, he had a good home and his brother was doing the same as he did but he got killed in the - in the war, first world war but Bill Evans to this day is a manufacturing chemist but he's gone blind.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You don't remember anybody going down in the world?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 One or two, but they killed themselves with drink. Drink did it, yes. There was one or two - men that worked at the Co-op shop.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Do you remember anyone being described as a real lady or a real gentleman and why do you think it was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
A real lady? Oh Enys Street, always respect - Bob Ogden, yes, I was taking him for being a gentleman. He was office worker and he was always nice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Why - was it because he was on office worker?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well - he was always well dressed and he was very pleasant.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You attach a lot to being well dressed don't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Yes. Yes. Yes. Goes a long way with me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Why?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 And the mind - and the ways he had. If I get a person that - abrupt, you - I go against him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You wouldn't think of them as a real lady or a real gentleman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Well, I treat them the same way then, I - I turn abrupt. I - I fight 'em back and anybody spoke to me abrupt anywhere if I went on a job later on in life and I met 
a managing director of firm and he spoke sharp to me I'd speak sharp back to him. I always put - anybody was nice with me I treated him very nice. That was -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Do you remember anyone being called a real lady in Whit Lane?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well the old Mrs - Mr Hughes's wife.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Why was she called a real lady?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 She was - gentle. Very gentle. Yes. Used to call her a lady. Yes, she was gentle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Do you remember seeing a policeman where you lived and how do you think he treated the people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well - well there was one time - that was on Cross Lane that, we got done.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you see a lot of policemen round Whit Lane?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well there was a - there was a Mr Blakely that lived - and children that lived two doors away from me, did you ever know Mr Blakely? M
ight have been before your time, remember him, he lived two doors away but he was - nobody had any respect for him. And during the miners strike I think it was they - they used to come strolling in his house and fighting and that -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 And he was a policeman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
He was a police Sergeant. They stoned his house, broke all his windows for him and then - during the - later on he got knocked unconscious up in Higher Broughton, I think that must have been his beat, they found him unconscious - somebody had at
tacked him up there and they always put it down to the miners.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Why was he so disliked?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well he was so - using his authority.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 How do you think the police treated the people generally though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well they - they - as I said there's that - 
those two detectives nobody had any respect for at Lane and - and - nobody had any respect for them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Why do you think it was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Used to think that they was - he was too slimey so and so's. They used to take them with being deceitful, these two Lan
e because least bit of thing they - you was - taken, yes. Makes no sense
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did your father ever say if you did anything wrong, I'll tell a policeman?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Never. Never, no, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 So you were\rquote nt actually afraid of the police as a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No. 
No, I remember when I was a bit older, when was about twenty going down Cross Lane and getting on Eccles Old Road we - when they had the monkey run. We stood in the door hole, there was four of us and was - must have been about nineteen. And - two detecti
v
es came up and - got hold of us and - said we was jumping on girls backs. And then - the other two come - our other two friends came up and they got hold of them and - they marched us up Cross Lane then. Then the constable - what was - what was the matter
 but they put in Cross Lane cell. Yes. And we got - proper what stripped, this is on the Sunday night. And we never had any respect for the police after that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 This was a false charge?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 And we - we marched up Cross Lane, all of us, four detectives 
and four young men. I was taken to Cross Lane station and - everything taken out - off us and - marks - anything identification marks and - then was pushed in the cell, took our heights and everything, pushed in the - in the cell up there and then we had 
t
o get bailed out. Eight people had to come and bail us out, parents plus the next door neighbours. The pound bail. And we got out at midnight. Then next - on the Monday morning was at - Cross Lane - at Salford police station - court. We all got fined a po
und a piece. In those days that was a lot. Which nowadays - four of us in a cell.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 How did they treat the people as a whole though, the police?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well I always thought - police had - I think they was a bit keen doing their duties such as down Whit L
ane. But - people down Whit Lane had no respect for the police. No. Although they went to the police when there was fighting going on but - I never thought they had much - much respect for them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Was your home rented and did you ever see the landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
No. Oh, the rent it was cost - costly landlords then. Yes, I used to have to wait in every - oh Monday or when - when they came and same as the club collector. Half my life was waiting in for the rent man coming or the - the penny a week club is it, 
the Prudential. I had - I had to wait in many - matter - couldn't go way. And for holidays, we never had a holiday. Never holiday up to about sixteen. Sixteen my holiday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you go away on Bank Holidays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Never. Birthday present. When me sister got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3093926 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 , I'm just saying, me twenty-first birthday me father give me a watch, it was from Blackpool in one of these auctioneers. It's supposed to be rolled gold.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You never went away for a holiday and you never went away for Bank Holidays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 N
ever. The only time we had a day was Whit week when we went with Sunday school and we used to go in one of these - cart things with forms on. Wagonette. And - and - not wagonettes - ordinary cart with forms out of the Sunday school all tied on. And then t
here was a rope round so you couldn't fall off, horse and cart.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You went to Enys Street, that was Methodist?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 That was a Meth - that's my - mother went to. I was supposed to be christened there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did your father go to chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 I can't remember him going to chapel, no. Me sister went, me sister was going there 'til she died at seventy-seven Enys Street.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You were telling me about this outing on the cart?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 We used to go to - we used to go to about Worsley, that were limit. That was - that was far as -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 What happened when you got there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Well they'd taken a big field and give you a - they did give you orange and - in a paper bag and a - a pie. And that was only outing I ever got.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did they have other social activities in the chapel and did you take part in them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 I never took part but we used to have concerts - fellow named Lenny Webb used to run a concert and he used to run -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 He was a councilor eventually wasn't he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 He was. Yes. Do you know him? Lenny Webb
. He's used to run - he used to train them at their - house in Indigo Street, he lived in Indigo Street. He didn't get }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3093926 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
 while late in life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did they have a temperance club do you know at Enys Street and did you ever sign the pledge?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Yes. I never signed the pledge but they had a temperance club.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Were you in it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you belong to the choir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you belong to any other clubs organised by the church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No. I just belonged to the football club and that was - and why I went to the church - chapel then is that the - so I could play football.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you say prayers at night as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Yes, I did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Who taught you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Nobody. I taught myself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you say grace at meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you keep any livestock at all or grow any vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No, none at all, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 How many times a week would you say you ate meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Meat - I think it was only once a week. That'd be on a Sunday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You didn't get any extra like rabbit from poaching?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No. Odd time we might have a rabbit when you could get rabbit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 But not from poaching?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you ever have tinned meat at all as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Boiled mutton. Used to have hash. Boiled mutton - plenty of boiled mutton in tho
se days and cold meat. Used to make hash, used to have hash.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did your sister or father ever go short of food so that you children could have more? Do you remember anyone going short of food at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No. I don't think - no. I can't - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Were you allowed to talk during meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Could you choose what you wanted or did you have to have what was put in front of you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Oh we had to have what was there. You know, what you was having you'd got to buy it - I used to go for it. I used to go to the chip shop.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you have to clean your plate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 It was always left - it was always clean. Not much on it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You were still hungry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well there was never much on in -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 If there was something on the table you wanted such as he salt, did you have to ask for it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Oh I didn't - no such things of asking, just - go and get it yourself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Could you ask for a second helping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Never. We never had knives and forks. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You said you couldn't ask for a second helping, were you taught to sit at the table in a certain way and did you have your own places at table?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No. Anywhere.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Were you taught to sit in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Could you bring toys or a book to the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Never had any toys. Never knew what toys were.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Could you leave the table when you wanted?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You didn't have to ask?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No, anywhere - any time - never asked.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did the family all sit together for certain meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Who served the meal and who was served first?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Oh God, who served up - yourself, you just get up and get your own. There's no serving - there's nobody to serve it. You know, I can remember if you had any company the children was left in the other room and the grown ups h
ad theirs first like on a Sunday, Sunday tea times, you ever invited anybody, which wasn't so often, any relation happened to come and have tea - believe there's only enough for that relations, those that were left in the room hardly got anything. There'd
 be no cake left. Can remember, used - looking round the door, hope she doesn't eat that piece of Russian sandwich there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 So the family had to hold back when you had visitors?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Yes. And - the younger part of the family like, self and me brother. A
nd you'd be peeping round the door well there's nothing left for us. You'd have what was left and it never - never be much. Not same as today, they can buy plenty but - if you had a - a Russian sandwich you was lucky on a Sunday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Where did the younger children sit before they were old enough to sit at the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Well I was the younger one. I was a youngster. I was going to say then. When me sister was courting and that they used to come - they used to go to the town like the two sisters, both cou
rting about the same time and - used to go to town and on the way back they'd call at such as Lewis's and bring a half a pound of ham and fry that and I'd only be youngster and they'd send me for Russian sandwich, this is when the shops is open all eleven
 
and twelve o'clock on a Saturday night. And if you got a whole one - a whole one he'd - he'd have extra piece. Oh no, if you got six pieces you'd have extra piece. I think they used to cut 'em up in six pieces, sandwiches. And if you - I used to like, enj
o
y - if he wanted a whole one it'd be a piece for me and I used to sit on the stairs when they're cooking up the supper I'd be sat on the stairs looking on the - never got any you know, 'cos they was courting and they wanted you out of the way and I spend 
half of my time before I went to bed sat on the stairs. That was one of me peculiar habits.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Why did you sit on the stairs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 I don't know. I always did that, when I went - going upstairs I was sat on the stairs, and sit there. Oh I always had a dr
awer in the - in the table, you know you have two drawers, one for knives and forks and I always had my toy drawer there so you can just imagine what my - always kept me - well I saved up and I used to have a book. Save penny up, save tuppence up, and rec
k
on it all up I might have about five and six and - bought a bicycle pump, one and three, and - write it down. And every so often when I was sat on the stairs you'd rattle it, you see. Yes, you know I was very - was a beggar for saving when I was a young m
an - youngster.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Was your father an easy person to talk to and could he showaffection?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 He was all right. Oh yes. He was easy - he was easy going. He was one of the best. As I say, he was like me brother. He's one of the best.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Was he able to show affection?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well I don't know, I don't think he did. He never - we never got hit with him but he never - never got a -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Could you share your worries with him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No, no, he never put his arm round you and anything like that. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Were you taught to behave towards your sister and brothers in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 I was taught - never taught anything like that. It was just -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 If another child hit you, were you told to hit back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Oh well, that naturally came with me. Anybody hit me -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Would your father tell you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No, no. Me father was never - no. No, I could hold me own then when I was a young - when I was a boy. It was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 What kind of a person do you think your father hoped you'd grow up to be, what did he think was important in life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Well he always wanted me to be - to have a - a decent job, a tradesman, that was in those days was something to be tradesman wasn't it, he always liked to be tradesman. He thought that was important, yes. Don't think he ever bothered 
about anything else because - I wanted to learn the piano but couldn't afford to have me taught and I taught meself so much then finished.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You had a piano at home did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 We had an old piano, we had it for years and years and years. But me sis
ter could play it but when it come to me but - we had no money for me - learning - me sister had - played.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you ever make music as a family, sing-songs or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No. Well - no. Now and again you might have a bit of a sing-song - 
but very rare we had any visitors. Only I can remember having a - having visitors when me sister got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3093926 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
 and all sat in the front place, what they call the parlour and that was her wedding. We had a bit of a sing-song there and there was only about a dozen in the front place so I cleared off to Manchester then on the trams.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 What did your father think of swearing, were you allowed to swear?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Oh never liked you swearing, no, very - there's no bad language used in the house. Never heard anybody swear.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Suppose adults were talking were you allowed to join in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No, couldn't - no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 If you did something your dad disapproved of how did he punish you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Oh he'd - he'd tell you of it but it were never got - never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Do you never remember an occasion when you were punished and what you felt about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
I only got told - only got told off once. That was when somebody had - had a load of coal delivered - a ton of coal delivered at the front door and a lot of the bass had come righ
t and I thought they'd put it at front of our door 'cos this woman's a vindictive woman that - two doors away and I threw it back. You know, being a young - I threw it back on the coal and she saw me doing it the lady two doors away and she pulled me fath
er up coming home from work. That was only time he ever spoke about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You were telling me about coal last time, can you tell me about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 A ton of coal. Used to get a ton of coal on the front doorstep. They'd deliver at the front door and you h
ad to carry it in buckets down the - the lobby - we used to call it the lobby - and the coal place were underneath the stairs and you'd have to dup it there, ton of coal. Oh it was a pound a ton then. And - as I get on in years I had a motor bike in that 
lobby, so you can just imagine people getting in and out with a motor bike stuck in that lobby. With a ton of coal.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did your father play games with you at all as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Were there books in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Newspapers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
We had books - oh we'd have a newspaper. They was only prizes what - you - were in the house, like Sunday school prizes and day school prizes when they used to give them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Do you ever remember your father reading and did he ever read out loud?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No. I never - I never remember me father - newspaper, never saw him read a book. Never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You never remember him reading out loud at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No. Oh never read out loud, no. Yes, yes, that is so. Oh you'd not - hadn't got to read the paper. No, oh no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Do you remember a funeral in your family, who attended and what kind of clothes they wore?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 I can't remember that - not me mother, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Do you remember a funeral at all - relatives or anyone, what it was like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well it was alwa
ys black wasn't it, in those days. It was - you couldn't go to a funeral without you had black on. Everything had to be black barring the shirt.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You don't remember a funeral at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No. No. Before they put the coffin up - before they put the lid on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Will you tell me that again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Anybody died in the street and - they used to have the coffin in the front place or - more often than not in the front place and all the neighbours used to come and up to view before they put the top - the lid on first.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you ever do this as a child?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Yes, I've done it. I used to be frightened stiff. I'm still fright - I don't - I used to do it, yes, I don't like going in a dead room now. I know when me father died at me sister's and - me brother and
 I, this was only few years ago and - he died with - cancer of the throat. I've heard the people putting a - on the dead body before they put the lid on, a plate of salt on to keep it from swelling.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 To keep the stomach from swelling?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Yes, keep the stomach, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Any other odd habits like this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No, I don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Do you ever remember a funeral in the street and what happened, neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well they all had the blinds drawn. - And - they all used to stand outside at the doors. Re
spect, and they all had collections for the - a wreath.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Round the neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 All the neighbourhood - all the neighbours in the street, they always had a collection, put a wreath on the - on the coffin.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Do you remember in the district where
 you lived if anyone did anything that people disapproved of how they showed their disapproval, say a man or woman did something that the neighbours considered wrong how did they show their disapproval?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Never remember that, no. No. No. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Were you ever taken visiting friends, neighbours or relations and who took you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Oh I was taken a time or two with me father to an old aunt of his in Radcliffe. Used to catch the tram and - go on the tram from - near the racecourse there and have a trip to Radcliffe.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Were you ever taken shopping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
No. Never. Yes, I used to go shopping with me sister when we was going for the groceries for the weekend to the tic shop. And we used to get a bar of chocolate, ha'penny bar of chocolate on the - on 
the grocery bill. He - that was - that was added on to the bill, that was it. Might have been penny or - used to be that - block - bright - dark chocolate and they had ha'enny bars. We used to have a bar a piece, me sister and I. And it was added on to th
e bill but it had to be added so she couldn't tell.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 What would happen if he found out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 It'd be - he was so short of money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you ever go out with just your father apart from visiting relatives?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Only - now and again I know and again 
I went to the Central Hall picture house. With me dad, just on occasion on the Thursday night. And I think it was tuppence then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 How did you spend your Saturdays when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well - Saturday morning - at Saturday morning - Saturday mor
nings we'd - I'd be waiting for the old club collector coming and then after that I'd go, especially when I lived in Cook Street, one or two of me friends, the whole gang of us, the one that used to stand near the shop door, they had their - his mother an
d
 father's deaf and dumb and they used to come home on a Friday night drunk and - and what this young fellow used to do, rifle their pockets. Yes. Take so much out and on a Saturday afternoon he'd come that and - we'd all go for a walk then, along the rive
r
 bank, that was Irwell River, past Agecroft cemetery into - back of Rainslough and he'd buy a load of these cigarettes, Turkish, Russian, and buy a load of toffee, cakes and then we'd go along like lords along the river puffing away these fancy Russian ci
garettes, red tipped ones, golden tipped - and remembered going, you know, have a good feed. It was all stolen money. They'd never miss it. And then this Newbury was another one who used to be able to do the same, he used to steal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 This was the one who was always in trouble with the police?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
He was in trouble, now he'd steal out of the bicycle shop and he'd come with the lads and they'd - they'd have a treat every so often on stolen money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Why was he always in trouble with the police, was it because he always stole from his father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 He - he was - a wrong one really, I think it was in him. And his home life were terrible.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 What did you do on Sunday, did you have different clothes to wear?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 They used to take 'em to the pawn shop then on a Monday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you have different clothes for Sunday though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No. It was about - nearly all the same for me. Very rare I had any decent clothes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 But you remember the pawn shops do you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 I remember the pawn shops that used to be ope
n at five o'clock of a Monday morning. There'd be woman there with loads of bundles, all their neighbours, they couldn't go they have a certain woman taking all six or seven bundles there, and they'd be queuing up waiting for - Tuppins Pawn shop, for - so
 they could pawn them for next - 'til the following week while they got their wages then they'd take - bring them back for weekend.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 So it's costly really because they'd to pay interest on it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 They had to pay every time yes, and that was every - every week you'd see 'em queueing up there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you play games on Sunday or did your parents think it was wrong to work or play on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 The parents never - your parents never bother - me father never bothered. It was free and easy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 He didn't think it was wrong to work or play on Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
No, although I - although I went to Sunday school. With an old coat on that had been turned up. I used to wear other people's clothes, me brother's clothes. With being the young one of the family. I m
ight wear a jacket that had been - I'd turned it up to make it look respectable. I used to put big stitching in and stockings, I used to darn me own, stitch 'em up with a piece of cotton. I can't remember ever washing me feet. Honestly speaking I was so y
oung you know - never been brought up. It was only when I started going -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you always have second hand clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Nearly always. I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you never have new ones at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Very - the only time when I started work, me - me first suit, that's the only one I can remember having a decent suit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 What about shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Shoes? Is secondhand shoes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you have them for any special time of the year at all?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No, the only time I can remember when I just - before left me father bought me - took me to - place facing - Alkane Armitage, Clarkson
\rquote s and bought me a pair of shoes then, they had button - button up - in the shop, button up shoes. Bought me a pair of them, I was delighted, it was - forget what it was for. I think he'd backed a
 winner on the horses. He used to have sixpenny bets then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did he like a bit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Oh yes. And a drink.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did he attend races at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No. No, he used to go sixpenny bet.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did he go out to pubs at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well when he had any money he 
used to go in the - the Maypole and the Clarence but - he - he never had much with five children. If - they used to bring - that was - that was good chap he was. Drank at home because -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You wouldn't remember because your mother was dead would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 I - no, it was other people I noticed, used to see 'em with a jug. Always a pint of ale or quart.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 When your father wasn't doing his work how did he spend his leisure, do you remember what he did with his spare time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Ooh - I'm just wondering w
hat the old man did in his spare time. Oh - that was at Radcliffe that. Bowling. In the parks and bowling, he had nothing else for any other entertainment. And if he had sixpence and wanted it to go in a pub I think - I think they could get a pint of beer
 then for a penny or tuppence couldn't they. If he got sixpence he was all right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did he never take part in any sport or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 How many nights a week would he stay in with you children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well I don't remember him e
ver staying in. No. He always went out somewhere but - he might go to me aunt's, like his sisters but I can't remember him ever stopping in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Who looked after you in the evening then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Anybody. We never looked after, you just - I could go - I could go to bed any time I liked. Midnight.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Suppose your father came in and you weren't in, what would happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 He didn't bother. Christmas time I remember when we lived in Thursfield Street sitting on the doorstep Christmas Eve. And getting the pre
sents and all of this and that but - there's none for us. The old fellow gave me - the old chap -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 How did you feel about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well used to feel a bit - sat there - all the whole few of us waiting me father coming in, he must have gone in the Clar
ence for - being Christmas, being -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Do you never remember anything different at Christmas as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
I can never remember having a - no, can never - no, never, not as a child, no, I don't think we ever had anything like that. Never. Never had a birthday up to I was twenty-one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Do you remember your father being in a boot club or a sick club or a funeral club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well they - they used to have sick clubs he was in and - burial clubs. Penny a week and all like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You don't remember anything else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
No. And a club you could have for a cheque. You pay a shilling a week. Cheque clubs. Women used to run them. In the street. Clothing cheque clubs. You take your first shilling you could go and draw how much you'd put in like a pound or 
two pound and go and get a rig-out. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did your father take an interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Do you remember hearing him talk about it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 I heard him talk about it but - I - it was - it was only two parties, there are only two to join
 more often than not, it was a Conservative. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Do you remember why he held these views?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
No. No. The only thing he had no choice that's the only - he was a Labour man when Labour did come. He's a real Labour - he's a Conservative -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did he take part in any political activity?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No. Never. No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
In some places at that time men felt they risked losing their job or their house if they voted differently from their employers, do you know if your father felt himself under that kind of pressure to vote for a particular party?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well he could have done you know, that firm, he could have done.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 How did it apply with a firm like that, it was quite a big engineering firm wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 It wasn't - it was a carding firm, they made wire carding.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 How do you think they would put the pressure on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Oh they got the sack - sack them. There was no - there's no union in those days, they used to sack people. I -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You think that applied in politics too?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Oh yes, yes, yes. Yes. They had to vote - they had to vote - Conservative otherwise they'd be - out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You felt your father felt this pressure?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Yes, because I'd an uncle who did fifty years and - helped. Sacked.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Was it because of politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well - don't kno
w it's politics but he was a church going man, uncle of mine, he was different than mine, he was tee - staunch teetotaller but I think that was me father's vies, if you didn't vote Conservative you'd be sacked. And a man with five children - uncle of mine
 had no children. People used to be moved on hand carts.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Always?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Oh well you were that poor you see blooming hand cart with a load of furniture on going two or three times each to the new house. And time you get the sandbone man to remove for you
. He carries rags and he'd - he'd do your removing for you in his - in the evenings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did your father have a lot of friends?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Oh he had loads of friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did they come to the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No, but he had loads of - yes, on - on a Sunday morni
ng he'd always have couple of bottles of beer in. I'm talking about later on in life when things - brightened up me sisters at work. Always had a - they always - the always knew where they could get a drink of beer before opening time and they always call
ed at me fathers for a glass of beer. Always had two bottles in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 This was the only time he really entertained?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Yes. He entertained. Then after that they'd go out and have a - the local and have a drink.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 People say that in those days people made their own amusements, when your father had friends in how did they amuse themselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 They very -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did they make music?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No, they - he - this were on a Sunday morning, he never - I never remember friends ever coming, it's just the Sunday 
morning, one or two certain people, his boozing friends that used to call, local people. But - friends, never. I never remember anybody coming to our house. And out - he was never in. Then if we had any - me brothers'd bring their friends in, I was only y
o
ung, and our entertainment would be a - grab apple, cut a apple and put it in a bowl of water and ducking into that and that was our entertainment or having a game of ludo, draughts, that was our entertain - and I always had one of these steam - steam eng
ine. One with; methylated spirits.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You saved up and bought that yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 I saved up and bought that myself. Oh it was never bought me, I - I was one for saving up. I've always been for saving up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Your father had a struggle to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 He did have a struggle. It was - it was damned hard work. And then to come - up to me - up to me getting }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3093926 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 . I always paid him a decent wage, housekeep - me - wages was two pounds sixteen, I used to give him two pound a week, that was up to getting }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3093926 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662  1936.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 How did you feel about the hard times as a boy, looking a back?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
I think I thought it was terrible. I never had a good - childhood - school - schooldays, my schooldays was hopeless. Terrible. Never - had a decent breakfast, I never knew what egg and bacon was, breakfast, never. My sis -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you feel bitterly about it as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No. No, well I didn't - not as a child, no, I didn't know any different then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Your father was never ill or out of work though was he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You'd never have to go to anyone for help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
We never got any help. All the schools used to have - soup kitchens, but I never went there, I could never go because I was running errands. I had to come home from school and run the errands for when they came home from work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Were the soup kitchens for anyone?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
No, the school children. In the school, in the cellars but you was real poor then. I could - they could get their pair of shoes from school too, if you was really in - but - I
 could never stop at school 'cos I'd all these errands to do, see, everybody going out to work and the wages wasn't good then. Independent that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You never had to ask anyone for help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 How old were you when you first went to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Be five wouldn't it, five.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 What age did you leave?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Fourteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you go a full day right from the beginning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 I started full time. Six o'clock in the morning 'til -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you go to school at six?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No. Oh I thought - I was thinking when I left. Oh no, no, I went to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You started at five and at what age did you leave?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Fourteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Do you remember the time of starting school when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Nine o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 'til what time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Twelve.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 And then in the afternoon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Half past one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 What kind of a school was it, a church school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Oh no, it was a council. Wellington Street, council, yes. I've had slates. I've written on slates, yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 How did you get to school, it wasn't very far away was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No, just round the corner.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Where did you have your midday meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 At home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 There were no school dinners were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 What did you think of school, did you like it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No, I never - never liked school, never liked school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Why didn't you like it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 And I never liked work. I was never any good at school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 What did you feel about the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 There's only one teacher I ever got on with and that was Miss Hilton. I always got on and - s
he always - passed remarks how - what nice cheeks and I always had red cheeks, rosy cheeks and that must have been the attraction with her. I was her - I was her favourite and that was the only one, all the others was men and - men wasn't as - but she was
 my - and I was her -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 And you didn't like school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 I didn't like school, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did the teachers emphasise certain things as important in life, such as manners or tidiness or punctuality or ways of speaking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No, I can't remember - don't think they did, no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 If you did something the teachers disapproved of how did they punish you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Oh with a cane. Oh used to have - they always had a short cane and put your hand out and six strokes you got.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 What were the offences they gave you the cane for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You got - for the least bit of a thing. Yes, were very strict, specially the men teachers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You were boys and girls separate at Wellington Street wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Yes. And - and there was certain teachers - there was certain tea
chers though, there's a Mr Hewitt, he used to go down with the cane and - everybody was frightened of him but least bit of a thing he'd have the - have you at the front with your hand out. And the old saying was if you put some - rubbed rosin on your hand
 it'd break the cane. Never worked.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you get the cane a lot?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Oh I always got the cane, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You always went to Wellington Street school did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Yes. The only school I went to, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did your father take an interest in school at all, did he ever go to school or visit the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No. No. Never, no, no, no, he never - no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 At Wellington Street did all the children come from the same type of home as yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Or were some different backgrounds?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No, they was all - nearly all from - working class.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 They were all from poor homes were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
They'd just have one or two come from, as we thought, respectable - come from like - Littleton Road - Severalls Road, just had one or two but more often than not they was all real - poor.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Do you remember the teachers singling out some children for different treatment to others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well they - only for being dirty. Used to get some of the children that lived round Hawkins Street very dirty and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Then what happened?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
They used to bring them out and - oh never washed their neck and things like that or things creeping up their - used to bring at front of class and show them up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Do you ever remember any children being left out of things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Any - no, social, no, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Were there any gangs or groups in the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Well there's gangs outside the school but I don't think there's any gangs in the school. More often than not gangs outside 'cos I was in gang - gangs of boys.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Tell me about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Well I was in a gang, that's when we used to go - pushing - in these shop windows, pushing 'em through the windows, can - with a cane. Yet they was all decent - young men. It was always gangs then of - we knocked about with these young 
men that was going to be boxers off Eller Street. Gang like - one or two of the Irish boys that - boxed - I just forget their names now but - well there's Marchants - there was gangs that knocked about with the Marchant brothers, then there was other fell
ows that trained at Marchants, used to come dancing, there'd be whole gang then and - they'd - they'd frighten you, you had to be careful what you said otherwise you - they'd be on you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 What would they do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Oh they'd beat you up. Yes. They - give 
you a good hiding. Well I mean say, rip - same as they do in the time with that - with - hit you with a first. There was one or two who turned professional boxers now but they - they're old men now but - always - always found a gang of young men and there
 
was a head 'cos he was good at boxing. Always got these young men hanging round them. And you find them in the dance halls, the Empress. You always got gangs there. Gangs, yes, in a dance - there was always gang - there was a gong from, when we was Enys S
t
reet, when we went dancing, I'm talking about now when we started round the sixteen, always a gang and then there's the bigger boys, what they call the - like me brother's gang, was another gang, those two gangs at Enys Street. The older boys and the youn
g - we was the younger ones.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 What would these gangs do, what was the idea of these gangs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Oh of a Sunday night you'd go for your entertainment be a walk round, you'd walk round Cheetham Hill or walk round Eccles Old Road picking the girls up, wal
k round Hird Park, Chimney Pot park. And you'd be - that's about all you did, walking round. That was it - the only entertainment you had in those days. You'd been to a dance on Saturday night, then you'd been to Masacrees shop for ice cream or - then you
'd go to Lodge beer house when you got a bit older, think of your - glass of beer you'd be - fight anybody then. You'd go in that place from the Empress in the back way so nobody'd see you, you daren't go in on {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Broad Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, somebody might see you and repor
t you to your father. You went the back way. And then - then we ever went to a dance hall down - Eccles Wheest, the Premier. We'd go in there - Widows Retreat. Well the Widows Retreat's the pub at the corner of Wheest Lane.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 This was when you'd left school was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
This is when I left school, when I got a bit older and got a bit more mannish then and started knocking about, dancing. And we'd go in the Widows Retreat, what they call the Widows Retreat, they'd all buried their husbands and they used 
to go in there drinking their sorrows. That's why it got called Widows Retreat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 When you left school did you still stay at home after you started work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 I stayed - I stayed at home 'til I was - thirty-five - five. When I got round the thirty mark
 and I was working long hours at - I didn't have much pleasure, it was all work, when I started work. That's why I never liked the shop. I was never at home when I was a young man. It was all weekend work, breakdown work. Working nights. And I used to com
e, there'd be no meals ready for me, then me - had - me sister down - she'd got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3093926 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
, used to go down in Hird Street, I'd have me midday meal there. Me sister's. She's died. But after that - there was no meals. Tea time I had - I'd be on me way home with
 a brown loaf. I'd get a brown loaf, I'd have that for my tea. I was a beggar for brown bread as I - I got to be a health friend - brown bread, cleaning me teeth every morning, never eating between meals. Used to come home with two or three pound of apple
s and put them in the drawer and there's me brother and me father, there three of us at home then, they all got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3093926 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
, there was three of us and we had an old set of drawers I used to have a drawer then, still had the old - under the table with the - I us
ed to get three pound of apples at one and a penny a pound - three pound from Overfields, bring them home. Have apple in the morning before me breakfast which was not much. And - I used to be -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Would you have stayed longer at school do you think if you'd had the chance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No, I don't think I would.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you go to evening school after you left?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 I went to the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Salford{\*\xmlclose} I went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}John Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} then - {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}London Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}John Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Evening school, I did me best.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 What did you do at evening school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 At night school - engineering. On three nights a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 For your City and Guilds was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No, it was - no, it was - second year, what they call second year, first year, second year and third year there. And - like first year 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}London Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} or {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}John Street{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. But apart from the night school I was coming home up to eighteen and running errands - for the teas. I used to do all the shopping. See, only three of us at home, me brother'd got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3093926 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 . The oldest brother was at home, me sisters had got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3093926 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
 and I used to be running errands, I'd be shopping in me dinner hour.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 So you didn't have much of a life really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Not much of a life, then it come later on as - working, always working week - always working. Overtime, break - with it b
eing a breakdown shop used to work nights, all night through the night, traveling, going these cotton mills. There was no such things as canteens in those days. It was all - buy a pie or work through the night with nothing. I can remember working at Green
woods, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Trafford{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Park{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 there, we had a breakdown job and a- just have you at the shop, go with Jim Coleman, the breakdown at Green woods, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Trafford{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
PlaceType}}Park{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. You'd had no tea, you'd get the tram and go and work, you'd be working right through the night, nothing to
 eat. They hadn't provided a thing for you. You work all night. You come home next morning, yet you had to the job had got right so you could get in the shop. You'd get in the shop you could go home then. Then the following day start again - and you'd wor
k another whole night getting all back stuff - so you get the job for the cotton - flour mill going. And that was all through my life. I was never at home when I got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3093926 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 . Away every weekend working overtime. And when I was a young man you couldn't say, 
I'm going to play football for the - for the chapel today or - you're working this weekend. You were on, and that was the way it went through.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you have any regrets about your education? And do you think you benefited from attending school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No, I'm - I liked to have - I'm sorry now - I have been - but I was never pushed - never had anybody to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Do you think you benefited at all from school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Oh I benefited, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Tell me what you felt about school looking back now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well I think it was a - you certainly needed schooling didn't you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 What did you feel about the teachers and education generally, your education?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well my education - it - it was all right but I never got far. And when I got in standard seven I thin
k it was only just a matter about being put - going up with the class, I don't think I got there on me own merits. I think it was just a matter of they couldn't leave you down when you was ready for leaving school, they had to put you in standard seven - 
they couldn't left you number, in - in five and you was going to work. I think I was pushed there. I think I was automatically, I don't think I was ever - I don't think the teachers those days ever took much -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Interest in you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You felt you were just a number or something?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You were just a number, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 While you were at school did you have a part time job or any means or earning a little extra money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No, I never - no, I never took papers, anything like that. No. Some of the
 boys used to take papers and - but - I had enough to do at home, I could never have a part time job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Tell me about your working life, you started off as an apprentice?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did the job alter your attitude to school when you became an apprentice?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Well - I kept going to night school and trying and then I - I got to the Salford Tech. and I kept on going there. What with this working overtime I didn't get more than second year at the Tech.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did it alter your attitude to your father when you started full timework?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No. None whatever, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Or with your brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
No. I used to hate me father for getting me at this firm, I never liked the firm, and I was there fifty years. But I used to come home heartbroken and I never - the firm was to me - I was there -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You were there fifty years and you went out on maintenance jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Yes. I was taught to be a fitter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Looking back at your working life what do you feel about it as a whole?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Now I - I - I tho
roughly enjoyed it. Now when I look back - bear in mind I later - it had its ups and downs - later I thought I had a very interesting job. When I come to think now. But bear in mind it was a rough job then. But later on in life where you had a bit - thing
s
 had got better with - between the management and your - conditions improved we - where we was going finding digs when we went working out at any poor old home. Later on you could get in hotel. Now years ago there was no such things as hotels. And when yo
u
 went on a job if it was at Rochale I'd have to be there for eight o'clock in those days, that meant you was turning out at six and you wasn't - you wasn't being paid for it. You was only being paid from starting on the job. Your traveling time you was gi
ving to them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You said you served your apprenticeship and then you had to leave, where did you go then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well - I was - I went to the bonding warehouse in Chapel Street, me brother was a foreman there, a chargehand like.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 What was that generally?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 I was labouring. I took up labouring.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 What was the bonding warehouse?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 It was a - the bonding warehouse.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Customs and Excise?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Yes. In Chapel Street. It's still there. I had to turn labouring otherwise I'd have been out of wor
k. And when - when I was at home I had to pay me dig money. If I were off sick - I was never off sick but if I had an accident which I had with that finger I was off for three months with that, I give him all my - me union - me union money and me club mon
ey. Thirty-six shilling a week and I made it up to two pound, so I was the loser, he wasn't the loser. I paid two pound dig money out of two pound fourteen. That was - that was 1930 - that was 1930 when that happened, see. But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You left school at fourteen and then you were apprenticed for how many years?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Seven.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 So that would bring you beyond 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Twenty-one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 When you started work did it change your attitude to life, did you alter your habits as a whole, did you still go to Sunday
 school when you started work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
No, we went to - no, we went to Sunday school while we went to Sunday school, we had a football team when we was young, round the twenty mark - eighteen and nineteen and it - you had to go to Sunday school to be in the 
- and it was the only social life we had then, apart from the dancing which - if we ever went to the Empress old Mr Hughes then, he was very strict, he got to know and he used to come, we used to get told off over it, not going such places, the Empress da
nce hall.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Why?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Such a common place. It was only sixpence for a dance there and it was a real common place, near Hankey Park, Church Street. And old Mr Hughes never liked it and always somebody used to tell tales that all the lads had gone - started going to the Empress.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You were a good dancer were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 I'm not so bad. We dance - I've danced all me life and I've sung all me life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you make new friends when you started work or did you still keep the old ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No, no, we stil
l kept together, the old - young chap from the school, he died with consumption at twenty. There was still - one died with cancer at nineteen, but the other friends - yes - the other friends, fellow name Bert Taylor, he went to South America, then a fello
w named Joe Redford, he's died. I'm the only one that's left. Well we all kept together, the whole - the whole gang from Enys Street.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You started going out with girls now did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Oh yes. Well - although we - I was going out with girls when I was going to school. In a way, yes. Yes. When I was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Yet you didn't get }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3093926 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
 'til late?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
No. But I was always fond of the - the opposite sex, always round the girls. I always - yes, I can remember when I was at school used to go round - this wa
s before - when we removed there I - and down Littleton Road at school going with girls down there. You know, used to get together and if you kissed 'em you thought you'd done wonders.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You thought you were a real lad.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Yes. But I - but I was always a bit shy, but I always liked the opposite sex.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did your father expect to know where you were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 And did you have to be in at a certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No. No. Time was no - oh - no, I used to get told off many a time for coming in late
. Used to climb through the bedroom window. Then me - I could get through the bedroom window. This is when we got older. And - if many a time I had no key, forgot me key and other time we went round the back and he'd locked the back bedroom window, had to
 
waken him up about twelve or two o'clock in the morning, he'd play hell then with us. That's all me - say - but - which anybody would if they got wakened up but more often than not we could climb over the bed - the - the backyard, over the wall, up the sh
ed and we could get through the bedroom window, it was nearly always open, and get in that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did he expect to meet your friends, was he keen on this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 He didn't bother about who I went with but - friends used to come for me. We never had a tabl
ecloth on, it was always a newspaper. Yes, always a - never a - I can't ever remember having a tablecloth - we might have had one like later on in life if we had company but through the week it was always a newspaper. No such things then, we had to keep t
he work down for me sisters 'cos they was working then and coming home from work six o'clock in the morning.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did you take an interest in politics as you grew older?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well - as I got older I got very friendly with a chap named Curley and his broth
er was a Registrar for Salford. And he was the big pal of Ted Hardey, a Labour - well - he - he was a Mayor Wasn't he? Well I - knocking about with Curley I - Labour - although I've been Labour, me father was Labour and I've been Labour.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Before 1918 as you were growing up did you take an interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Well - as Labour came in, yes, I used to go watching all - the old M.P. for Salford - who did Billy Aspin mention - the old M.P. that used to - I used to go down to the old Regent, listen to
 meetings on a - you know, council - big meetings. Oh there was an old - just a minute now - father was Labour, we was all - there was two of us Labour - there's three of us knocking about at one time and was - there's two of us Labour and the - the offic
e
 man was Ted - Bert Taylor, he was Conservative. Red hot, and we was Labour. We used to have arguments like hell. I', trying to think the old - these M.P., he used to be giving you - at all the schools but - like now there's no such things as meetings is 
there. It's all on the television now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 When you left school and went to work did it change your attitude to life in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 I - it changed mine because - as I got a bit older I started having a - like with working at weekend and - I started bein
g able to dress up and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You do put an importance on dress don't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Yes. I - I was always one - soon as I got working and I - I was always making really good money then. Working this overtime, I was always one for dress. And my friend that was
 a Conservative and he had a good job in South America, he always were dressed the way I dressed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Do you think this was because you never had clothes as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 I think it was, yes, yes, and some money in me pocket, but I was always one for - a
 steady chap. And it - I'd go down Cheetham Hill to Showman\rquote s or Levine\rquote s and get a good suit and I always had two or three suits a year when I was young, I was always one - and always looked after me teeth, I always had smashing teeth.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Tell me about your childhood as you remember it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Well me childhood was really - it wasn't a childhood. I wouldn't like anybody to have same childhood as I had. Bear in mind I was never ill treated.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You had a kind father didn't you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 I had a kind father 
but he never took any interest but - you can't have it both ways but - me childhood was - the pleasures, I'd none. I say all the other young lads I knocked about - they had their mothers, always nice and clean, well fed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You missed your mother terribly did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Must - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You told me she ran a tripe shop and she died of consumption?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Do you remember or did you hear anything about it - the treatment, what happened to her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Well I don't know. I believe that in those days
 when - they - in a tripe shop they had to - put the tripe in these big wash tubs and - I believe in the winter time and it - you had a covered yard, I remember that, and these - and they used to put the tripe in there and they had to put their hands, you
 know, cold - icy cold there and I - I - M always heard me sisters that that was the cause of her - then having five children in such a short time and trying too look after shop, must have been a job mustn't it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 She must have worked very hard?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Must have worked hard - having five children in such a short time. Six children, one died at - so she had six children then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Was it stillborn?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 I couldn't just say bit I believe - I - I'd always heard I'd had a sister called Bertha, I don't know. B
ut me sister, our Jane seventy-seven, then our Ethel was seventy-six isn't she now, that must have been - and then me brother, our Fred, he's seventy-odd. Seventy-four. And then me brother here seventy-two. And there was one in between, the one that died 
- I never knew. And then the brother of seven - going on for seventy-three. And I'm going on for sixty-nine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 So your mother had a hard life didn't she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 And trying to run a shop. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 How did she go on if she had consumption and she had the tripe shop, did she have to come out of it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Well I think she had to come out then. But I think she died there. Think it was what they called in those days galloping consumption. They didn't last long did they, what with no food. And me father only on 
a poor wage. I think the wage were only about thirty bob a week then. I - I heard him, I used to hear him say that - when he'd paid all his debts he had nothing in his pocket. He used to go to old Johnny Walton the milkman and ask him to lend him sixpence
.
 And put it on the bill. I've heard that said a time or two. Then we left there and went in Thursfield Street. And that's when we used to sit on the doorstep Christmas Eve. The old man must have got a - a bob or two and gone in the Clarence and me sister 
w
as looking after us so he thought everything was all right and we sit on the doorstep waiting for him - but I never knew what Christmas Day was. And I must have been about twelve before I ever bought myself a present and that was always a gun. Or somethin
g like that. Sixpence ha'penny - I remember that, that was sixpence ha'penny, that was a toy and then me old little steam engine. That was my -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 What do you think generally then looking back, do you think they were good old days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No, I - no, I th
ink they're terrible. There was no good old days. When I come to think of it when I started work the long hours I pushed in, for a boy. Was no - you had to work overtime when you was young - there was no age limit. Well when I was - when I started work we
 
worked overtime, the war started. There's no limit. I was working overtime and trying to go to the night school. No wonder you miss your education. And it was one of these cases when everybody was - they'd bring a job at that firm then, a man'd carry it i
n
 a lodge and they'd do it. And he'd - they didn't give a toss about the men or boys, they - you'd have to work all night to get the job done for them. And the man'd still be waiting there. You was never considered. I didn't call that the good old days. No
. Now - they're used now. They're not allowed to do this, they're not allowed to do that. I - I had a good hiding many a time off a man, if you happened to say a word to him he'd -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 This was when you were an apprentice?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 When you was apprenticed, y
ou said a word to him - or if you didn't go up for the grindstone when you sharpen it the foreman'd give you a back hander, you'd got to wait - you had to respect the man, the fitter. But there's no such - but now you daren't touch 'em now. They're pamper
ed these days, apprentices. Good God, they go - they go to school - they're going to school, never - never find them - never seem to take any interest, we just wandered round, we'd go and - get in -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Because he'd never had any himself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Your dad had a hard childhood did he?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
He must have had a hard childhood, yes. Well they did in those days hadn't they. But we used to go in gangs or we used to play on the river when I lived near the river and it was all - nearly all my time -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Children used to get drowned in the river in those days didn't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Yes, they would have done but he never knew where I was. I used to wander off. He was - either out. We used to - honestly speaking I don't know why I'm living today because we u
sed to play on that river when it was flooded. Have you ever seen the River Irwell flooded. It goes fast. And many a time we used to play near that reservoir, at the weir what they call and many a time we used to go underneath that bridge facing the - fac
i
ng the - the racecourse and we used to get - I've seen them riv - the river - as high as the bank - level - flooding over that field. And we've go on there, there's all sand, and we've gone walking on the edge and I think many a time, well it's given unde
r us and we'd have gone in that river we'd have been drowned.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 A lot of children were drowned there weren\rquote t' they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 And we've - I used to do that in my child - and many a time when the river was down we used to go playing hours and hours on that. A
nd I saw - once saw this river the river wasn't flooded, I saw my friend get - sailing down the river with a current, bear in mind it wasn't flooded then, he'd have been drowned, but he happened to scramble out. But that's what got me swimming, that time.
 I still swim. When I was about ten. I - I'm still frightened of water. I'm still frightened of water.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Considering you had such poor food as a child you've grown up very healthy haven't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 And I got - I had - always had brown teeth. Now - I mus
t have had something - but it wasn't what we had, I don't know, I must have been born like that. But I'm only little. I might look well now, I've been in the sun.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You were telling me that you had alcoholic parents, tell me about it, what it was like to be a child of alcoholic parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
I can remember - I - about the age of six or seven lying in bed at night with four sisters. There at the top and two at the bottom. And they used to - I used to lie there, I couldn't sleep 'til they were coming. I 
used to listen for the sound of their footsteps coming round the back - down the back street by the - the nearer rhythm of the step I knew how much drink she'd taken. I could tell how far gone she'd - she'd be and I'd listen for the back door closing, usu
a
lly she came in talking to herself. And then he'd come in. And he - he was a good - he was a quiet drinker. When he'd had his drink he'd sit quietly and he - he was quite content to read the paper but she'd sit there and needle him and keep on and on 'til
 
in the end he'd get up and give her a wallop and then the pots would start flying and the finish up, there wouldn't be a thing in the house that wasn't broken and we used to lay there too terrified to move. One sister used to have nightmares. The other us
e
d to walk in her sleep. One developed St Vitus dance. It was called St Vitus dance in those days. Suffered with a nervous disease. But - and the times she left him. She got so tired of him, I don't know why, he was a club singer, he was quite a good singe
r. And - I've a silver cup in there that he won from singing. But - and she was a singer too.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 What drove them to alcohol?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 I don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Do you think they were ill matched?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 She - no, she was a - she was a very intelligent woman and she 
was so bored with her existence as a housewife and bringing five children, it was her way of escapism. And she went out and he was brought up strictly with old fashioned parents, he didn't approve of it. And I remember during the war when he was away in t
he '14-'18 war she used to bring soldiers in you know. She used to bring them in. And when I used to come down, I was quite - I must have been quite young - about eight, how old would I be -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You don't mind telling me do you, you said this is what made 
yours a happy marriage you'd both had a hard childhood, you don't mind telling me about it do you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Oh no, not at all, no. When I - and at school I'd no trouble. My form of escapism were books. And she was a heavy reader herself, my mother, and I read
 too. I read at - everything she'd finished with I used to go to the top of Corporation Park up by the big cannons in Blackburn and I used to sit there and there was a lady in one of the big houses there, she got to know me by sight. She used to come out 
a
nd bring me a pile of fairy tale books. And I used to go up once a week and she'd collect these and she used to bring - I used to go to jumble sales and buy them there at a ha'penny each. Books - I used to climb into the top cupboards to get hold of books
 
but mother put out of me road, about midwifery. She, at one time, had been a mental nurse. Reading was easy and I had a photographic memory. I had no trouble. At ten years old I was seven. They couldn't do anything with me. They put me in for a scholarshi
p.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You think you were highly intelligent, you took after your mother obviously?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
I - From Church of England Central School at Blackburn, this girl has great breadth of vision, should go far - that was the headmistress. I went to High School. I ha
d a good grandmother. My father's mother. I went to - I won a scholarship at ten, I couldn't take it while eleven, I went to High School, couldn't afford - parents couldn't afford to keep me there and - they sent me to the Cathedral school. Well - this - 
I couldn't have had better teachers. They gave me tickets for this I - I never had any trouble with them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Do you think this alcoholism had any influence on you as you grew older?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 I was an introvert. I was most unsociable. I distrusted everyone. I
 made friends with no one at all - I couldn't believe in anybody. And - and I - I'm a very cynical woman now. I'm a great believer in - believer in woman\rquote s rights you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Because of seeing what happened to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 I don't know, yes, maybe.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You think this drove your mother to drink do you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
I think so, yes. I went nursing and - she attempted suicide and they brought her into hospital where I was student nurse. Matron sent for me, she said, I think you'd better go on night duty nur
se, it'll be better for you, get this business over Put me on night duty. But the nurses knew you know. It was most unpleasant. But I had no trouble, I got through. She did it twice, yes, once -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 She died a natural death in the end?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Yes, with emphysema she -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Why do you think your father took to alcohol?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Probably because - probably because he was a club singer and he was - he was a club singer you see and - yes, they drank there yes. He won three - he won three of these. Had three of these. Yes, yes. He was - yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You told me that you'd had a very happy }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3093926 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662  life, both of you feel this was a result of your childhood do you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Oh we've - we've both appreciated each other, we've never - never had any trouble.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Mr Clay - If I'd have got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3093926 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662  at twenty I'd have been divorced hundred times. If I'd have -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Why?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 I was never settling type. As I said when I was young - I was fond of the girls and I'd have got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid3093926 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662  young, 'cos all the girls, I used to fall for 'em and they'd fall for me and I could have got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3093926 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662  - I could have got }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3093926 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
 umpteen times but - I wasn't the settling type and - get nearly engage - girls with plenty of money. Then I got the - chasing nurses.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 This is how you chased your wife?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
No, no, no. This is 19 - about 1924 and I used - and then - 19 - it was in 1930 I met Curly, started knocking about with him and then - that was nurse - I was always in - chasing the nurse - don't know why I fancied nurses. Then when I got about the thirt
y mark and was working these long hours and coming home and nothing in or me father might have left me some stew in the oven I thought I'll have to get - pack this game up. I want looking after.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Mrs Cay - And he used to bake apple pies and come and meet me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Mrs Clay - I used to bake them on Saturday afternoon. Apple pie at the Saturday night. Sunday mornings. Saturday night, bring a pie, meat pie I'd made.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Both having unhappy homes did you sit down and discuss it ever?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Mr Clay - No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 You didn't sort of go out to make your marriage happy because you'd had an unhappy background?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 K2  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Mrs Clay - no.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Mr Clay - No, no, because I'd met other girls I might - no, I'd met other girls I'd liked and thought, ooh I'm going to 
marry this one, but - as I say I wasn't the settling type. Although I was working long hours I used to go away from home. You know, meeting people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Your brother has a broken home?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 K2  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Mrs Clay - No. No, two of my sisters have broken - three of my s
isters have been divorced. Now there you are, you've got the pattern of a broken home repeating itself there. Three of them have had divorces.</subject2>
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Your mother and father were hopelessly unsuited were they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No. They weren't - they weren't 
unsuited because she was very fond of him. But she was a - she was a terror when she'd had some drink. She had a - and they were different religions of course too - she was a Roman Catholic.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 Did this cause trouble do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 No. She never went to church - gave it up entirely.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4729 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 This must have been terrifying for you as children though?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1665651 JC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1991662\charrsid1991662 
Terrified. Terrified. Oh yes, Irene had it worse than I did because - I - I grew hard as I got older and I - they put me to weaving, they put me to wea
ving, cotton weaving of course. Well automatically I went into a weaving mill when one was fifteen - fourteen or fifteen. I think it was about three and sixpence a week I got and - when I got to the four loom stage I thought, I'm going to be in here for l
i
fe. And I said to me mother one day, I'd like to get away from here, I'd like to go nursing. And she was very cooperative, she said, well you'll need five pounds to buy your uniform In those days one had to buy probationers uniforms for the first three mo
n
ths. She said, now I've not got five pounds but I'll go to your Auntie Rachel at Blackpool. That was father's sister. And she said, you'll have to think of something to tell your dad. So I told me father that we were going to come on short time. I was qui
t
e prepared to tell a thumping big lie to get out of this. And - we did that. She went to Blackpool, borrowed the five pounds, I told the old man that - we were closing down that it was going to be taken over, this big; mill. And - she bought the uniform a
n
d she came home and said that she'd found me a job and he wanted to know what it was and - she said, oh she's going nursing. Well he didn't - well, he said, it's not too bad as long as you send us - she told him what the salary was, it was very poor of co
u
rse, about two pound odd a month you know, if you'll send me a pound a month home out of that. Well I greed to do that and I did that. For the first four years. The last two years it was impossible because for the fifth year I was getting only forty-five 
p
ounds a year. I was doing midwifery and the last year I was doing fever nursing at Ladywell, also with me very poor salary. And then I went to Bach hospital, Staff Midwife and - I met him there. I was going in my way to take tropical diseases - yes, me wa
s going to go to Liverpool to take tropical diseases and go abroad to India but I never got past Salford.
